# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chemical
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chemical/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:chemical/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:chemical/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:chemical/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:chemical/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:chemical/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:chemical/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:chemical/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:chemical/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:chemical/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:chemical/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:chemical/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:chemical/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:chemical/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:chemical/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:chemical/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:chemical/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:chemical/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:chemical/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:chemical/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:chemical/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:chemical/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:chemical/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:chemical/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:chemical/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:chemical/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:chemical/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:chemical/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:chemical/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:chemical/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:chemical/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:chemical/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:chemical/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:chemical/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:chemical/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:chemical/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:chemical/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:chemical/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:chemical/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:chemical/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:chemical/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:chemical/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:chemical/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:chemical/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:chemical/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:chemical/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:chemical/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:chemical/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:chemical/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:chemical/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:chemical/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:chemical/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:chemical/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:chemical/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:chemical/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:chemical/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:chemical/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:chemical/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:chemical/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:chemical/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:chemical/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:chemical/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:chemical/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:chemical/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:chemical/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:chemical/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:chemical/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:chemical/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:chemical/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:chemical/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:chemical/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:chemical/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:chemical/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:chemical/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:chemical/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:chemical/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:chemical/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:chemical/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:chemical/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:chemical/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:chemical/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:chemical/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:chemical/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:chemical/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:chemical/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:chemical/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:chemical/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:chemical/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:chemical/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:chemical/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:chemical/chemical] In chemistry, a **substance** is a unique form of matter with constant chemical composition and characteristic properties.
[src:chemical/chemical] Chemical substances may take the form of a single element or chemical compounds.
[src:chemical/chemical] If two or more chemical substances can be combined without reacting, they may form a chemical mixture.
[src:chemical/chemical] If a mixture is separated to isolate one chemical substance to a desired degree, the resulting substance is said to be chemically pure.
[src:chemical/chemical] Chemical substances can exist in several different physical states or phases (e.g. solids, liquids, gases, or plasma) without changing their chemical composition.
[src:chemical/chemical] Substances transition between these phases of matter in response to changes in temperature or pressure.
[src:chemical/chemical] Some chemical substances can be combined or converted into new substances by means of chemical reactions.
[src:chemical/chemical] Chemicals that do not possess this ability are said to be inert.
[src:chemical/chemical] Pure water is an example of a chemical substance, with a constant composition of two hydrogen atoms bonded to a single oxygen atom (i.e.
[src:chemical/chemical] The atomic ratio of hydrogen to oxygen is always 2:1 in every molecule of water.
[src:chemical/chemical] Pure water will tend to boil near 100 °C (212 °F), an example of one of the characteristic properties that define it.
[src:chemical/chemical] Other notable chemical substances include diamond (a form of the element carbon), table salt (NaCl; an ionic compound), and refined sugar (C12H22O11; an organic compound).
[src:chemical/chemical] In addition to the generic definition offered above, there are several niche fields where the term "chemical substance" may take alternate usages that are widely accepted, some of which are outlined in the sections below.
[src:chemical/chemical] Chemical Abstracts Service (CAS) lists several alloys of uncertain composition within their chemical substance index.
[src:chemical/chemical] While an alloy could be more closely defined as a mixture, referencing them in the chemical substances index allows CAS to offer specific guidance on standard naming of alloy compositions.
[src:chemical/chemical] Non-stoichiometric compounds are another special case from inorganic chemistry, which violate the requirement for constant composition.
[src:chemical/chemical] For these substances, it may be difficult to draw the line between a mixture and a compound, as in the case of palladium hydride.
[src:chemical/chemical] In the field of geology, inorganic solid substances of uniform composition are known as minerals.
[src:chemical/chemical] When two or more minerals are combined to form mixtures (or aggregates), they are defined as rocks.
[src:chemical/chemical] Many minerals, however, mutually dissolve into solid solutions, such that a single rock is a uniform substance despite being a mixture in stoichiometric terms.
[src:chemical/chemical] Feldspars are a common example: anorthoclase is an alkali aluminum silicate, where the alkali metal is interchangeably either sodium or potassium.
[src:chemical/chemical] In law, "chemical substances" may include both pure substances and mixtures with a defined composition or manufacturing process.
[src:chemical/chemical] For example, the EU regulation REACH defines "monoconstituent substances", "multiconstituent substances" and "substances of unknown or variable composition".
[src:chemical/chemical] The latter two consist of multiple chemical substances; however, their identity can be established either by direct chemical analysis or reference to a single manufacturing process.
[src:chemical/chemical] For example, charcoal is an extremely complex, partially polymeric mixture that can be defined by its manufacturing process.
[src:chemical/chemical] Therefore, although the exact chemical identity is unknown, identification can be made with a sufficient accuracy.
[src:chemical/chemical] The CAS Registry also includes mixtures.
[src:chemical/chemical] Polymers almost always appear as mixtures of molecules of multiple molar masses, each of which could be considered a separate chemical substance.
[src:chemical/chemical] However, the polymer may be defined by a known precursor or reaction(s) and the molar mass distribution.
[src:chemical/chemical] For example, polyethylene is a mixture of very long chains of -CH2- repeating units, and is generally sold in several molar mass distributions, LDPE, MDPE, HDPE and UHMWPE.
[src:chemical/chemical] The concept of a "chemical substance" became firmly established in the late eighteenth century after work by the chemist Joseph Proust on the composition of some pure chemical compounds such as basic copper carbonate.
[src:chemical/chemical] He deduced that, "All samples of a compound have the same composition; that is, all samples have the same proportions, by mass, of the elements present in the compound." This is now known as the law of constant composition.
[src:chemical/chemical] However, there are some controversies regarding this definition mainly because the large number of chemical substances reported in chemistry literature need to be indexed.
[src:chemical/chemical] Isomerism caused much consternation to early researchers, since isomers have exactly the same composition, but differ in configuration (arrangement) of the atoms.
[src:chemical/chemical] For example, there was much speculation about the chemical identity of benzene, until the correct structure was described by Friedrich August Kekulé.
[src:chemical/chemical] Likewise, the idea of stereoisomerism – that atoms have rigid three-dimensional structure and can thus form isomers that differ only in their three-dimensional arrangement – was another crucial step in understanding the concept of distinct chemical substances.
[src:chemical/chemical] For example, tartaric acid has three distinct isomers, a pair of diastereomers with one diastereomer forming two enantiomers.
[src:chemical/chemical] An element is a chemical substance made up of a particular kind of atom and hence cannot be broken down or transformed by a chemical reaction into a different element, though it can be transmuted into another element through a nuclear reaction.
[src:chemical/chemical] This is because all of the atoms in a sample of an element have the same number of protons, though they may be different isotopes, with differing numbers of neutrons.
[src:chemical/chemical] As of 2025, there are 118 known elements, about 80 of which are stable – that is, they do not change by radioactive decay into other elements.
[src:chemical/chemical] Some elements can occur as more than a single chemical substance (allotropes).
[src:chemical/chemical] For instance, oxygen exists as both diatomic oxygen (O2) and ozone (O3).
[src:chemical/chemical] The majority of elements are classified as metals.
[src:chemical/chemical] These are elements with a characteristic lustre such as iron, copper, and gold.
[src:chemical/chemical] Metals typically conduct electricity and heat well, and they are malleable and ductile.
[src:chemical/chemical] Around 14 to 21 elements, such as carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen, are classified as non-metals.
[src:chemical/chemical] Non-metals lack the metallic properties described above, they also have a high electronegativity and a tendency to form negative ions.
[src:chemical/chemical] Certain elements such as silicon sometimes resemble metals and sometimes resemble non-metals, and are known as metalloids.
[src:chemical/chemical] A chemical compound is a chemical substance that is composed of a particular set of atoms or ions.
[src:chemical/chemical] Two or more elements combined into one substance through a chemical reaction form a chemical compound.
[src:chemical/chemical] All compounds are substances, but not all substances are compounds.
[src:chemical/chemical] A chemical compound can be atoms bonded together in molecules, or in crystals in which atoms, molecules or ions form a crystalline lattice.
[src:chemical/chemical] Compounds based primarily on carbon and hydrogen atoms are called organic compounds, and all others are called inorganic compounds.
[src:chemical/chemical] Compounds containing bonds between carbon and a metal are called organometallic compounds.
[src:chemical/chemical] Compounds in which components share electrons are known as covalent compounds.
[src:chemical/chemical] Compounds consisting of oppositely charged ions are known as ionic compounds, or salts.
[src:chemical/chemical] Coordination complexes are compounds where a dative bond keeps the substance together without a covalent or ionic bond.
[src:chemical/chemical] Coordination complexes are distinct substances with distinct properties different from a simple mixture.
[src:chemical/chemical] Typically these have a metal, such as a copper ion, in the center, and a non-metal atom, such as the nitrogen in an ammonia molecule or oxygen in a water molecule, forms a dative bond to the metal center, e.g. tetraamminecopper(II) sulfate [Cu(NH3)4]SO4·H2O.
[src:chemical/chemical] The metal is known as a "metal center" and the substance that coordinates to the center is called a "ligand".
[src:chemical/chemical] However, the center does not need to be a metal, as exemplified by boron trifluoride etherate BF3OEt2, where the highly Lewis acidic, but non-metallic boron center takes the role of the "metal".
[src:chemical/chemical] If the ligand bonds to the metal center with multiple atoms, the complex is called a chelate.
[src:chemical/chemical] In organic chemistry, there can be more than one chemical compound with the same composition and molecular weight.
[src:chemical/chemical] Isomers usually have substantially different chemical properties, and often may be isolated without spontaneously interconverting.
[src:chemical/chemical] A common example is glucose vs. fructose.
[src:chemical/chemical] The former is an aldehyde, the latter is a ketone.
[src:chemical/chemical] Their interconversion requires either enzymatic or acid-base catalysis.
[src:chemical/chemical] However, tautomers are an exception: the isomerization occurs spontaneously in ordinary conditions, such that a pure substance cannot be isolated into its tautomers, even if these can be identified spectroscopically or even isolated in special conditions.
[src:chemical/chemical] A common example is glucose, which has open-chain and ring forms.
[src:chemical/chemical] One cannot manufacture pure open-chain glucose because glucose spontaneously cyclizes to the hemiacetal form.
[src:chemical/chemical] All matter consists of various elements and chemical compounds, but these are often intimately mixed together.
[src:chemical/chemical] Mixtures contain more than one chemical substance, and they do not have a fixed composition.
[src:chemical/chemical] Butter, soil and wood are common examples of mixtures.
[src:chemical/chemical] Sometimes, mixtures can be separated into their component substances by mechanical processes, such as chromatography, distillation, or evaporation.
[src:chemical/chemical] Grey iron metal and yellow sulfur are both chemical elements, and they can be mixed together in any ratio to form a yellow-grey mixture.
[src:chemical/chemical] No chemical process occurs, and the material can be identified as a mixture by the fact that the sulfur and the iron can be separated by a mechanical process, such as using a magnet to attract the iron away from the sulfur.
[src:chemical/chemical] The resulting compound has all the properties of a chemical substance and is not a mixture.
[src:chemical/chemical] Iron(II) sulfide has its own distinct properties such as melting point and solubility, and the two elements cannot be separated using normal mechanical processes; a magnet will be unable to recover the iron, since there is no metallic iron present in the compound.
[src:chemical/chemical] In other words, the chemical substances of which fruits and vegetables, for example, are naturally composed even when growing wild are not called "chemicals" in general usage.
[src:chemical/chemical] In countries that require a list of ingredients in products, the "chemicals" listed are industrially produced "chemical substances".
[src:chemical/chemical] The word "chemical" is also often used to refer to addictive, narcotic, or mind-altering drugs.
[src:chemical/chemical] The cause of the difference in production volume is the complexity of the molecular structure of the chemical.
[src:chemical/chemical] Bulk chemicals are usually much less complex.
[src:chemical/chemical] While fine chemicals may be more complex, many of them are simple enough to be sold as "building blocks" in the synthesis of more complex molecules targeted for single use, as named above.
[src:chemical/chemical] The *production* of a chemical includes not only its synthesis but also its purification to eliminate by-products, impurities, and unreacted starting material involved in the synthesis.
[src:chemical/chemical] The last step in production should be the analysis of batch lots of chemicals in order to identify and quantify the percentages of impurities for the buyer of the chemicals.
[src:chemical/chemical] The required purity and analysis depends on the application, but higher tolerance of impurities is usually expected in the production of bulk chemicals.
[src:chemical/chemical] Thus, the user of the chemical in the US might choose between the bulk or "technical grade" with higher amounts of impurities or a much purer "pharmaceutical grade" (labeled "USP", United States Pharmacopeia).
[src:chemical/chemical] "Chemicals" in the commercial and legal sense may also include mixtures of highly variable composition, as they are products made to a technical specification instead of particular chemical substances.
[src:chemical/chemical] For example, gasoline is not a single chemical compound or even a particular mixture: different gasolines can have very different chemical compositions, as "gasoline" is primarily defined through source, properties and octane rating.
[src:chemical/chemical] Every chemical substance has one or more systematic names, usually named according to the IUPAC rules for naming.
[src:chemical/chemical] An alternative system is used by the Chemical Abstracts Service (CAS).
[src:chemical/chemical] Many compounds are also known by their more common, simpler names, many of which predate the systematic name.
[src:chemical/chemical] For example, the long-known sugar glucose is now systematically named 6-(hydroxymethyl)oxane-2,3,4,5-tetrol.
[src:chemical/chemical] Natural products and pharmaceuticals are also given simpler names, for example the mild pain-killer Naproxen is the more common name for the chemical compound (S)-6-methoxy-α-methyl-2-naphthaleneacetic acid.
[src:chemical/chemical] Chemists frequently refer to chemical compounds using chemical formulae or molecular structure of the compound.
[src:chemical/chemical] There has been a phenomenal growth in the number of chemical compounds being synthesized (or isolated), and then reported in the scientific literature by professional chemists around the world.
[src:chemical/chemical] An enormous number of chemical compounds are possible through the chemical combination of the known chemical elements.
[src:chemical/chemical] As of Feb 2021, about "177 million organic and inorganic substances" (including 68 million defined-sequence biopolymers) are in the scientific literature and registered in public databases.
[src:chemical/chemical] The names of many of these compounds are often nontrivial and hence not very easy to remember or cite accurately.
[src:chemical/chemical] Also, it is difficult to keep track of them in the literature.
[src:chemical/chemical] Several international organizations like IUPAC and CAS have initiated steps to make such tasks easier.
[src:chemical/chemical] CAS provides the abstracting services of the chemical literature, and provides a numerical identifier, known as CAS registry number to each chemical substance that has been reported in the chemical literature (such as chemistry journals and patents).
[src:chemical/chemical] This information is compiled as a database and is popularly known as the Chemical substances index.
[src:chemical/chemical] Other computer-friendly systems that have been developed for substance information are: SMILES and the International Chemical Identifier or InChI.
[src:chemical/chemical] Often a pure substance needs to be isolated from a mixture, for example from a natural source (where a sample often contains numerous chemical substances) or after a chemical reaction (which often gives mixtures of chemical substances).
[src:chemical/chemical] Stoichiometry (/ˌstɔɪkiˈɒmɪtri/ ⓘ) is the relationships between the quantities of reactants and products before, during and after chemical reactions.
[src:chemical/chemical] Stoichiometry is based on the law of conservation of mass; the total mass of reactants must equal the total mass of products, so the relationship between reactants and products must form a ratio of positive integers.
[src:chemical/chemical] This means that if the amounts of the separate reactants are known, then the amount of the product can be calculated.
[src:chemical/chemical] Conversely, if one reactant has a known quantity and the quantity of the products can be empirically determined, then the amount of the other reactants can also be calculated.
[src:chemical/chemical] However, the current equation is imbalanced.
[src:chemical/chemical] The reactants have 4 hydrogen and 2 oxygen atoms, while the product has 2 hydrogen and 3 oxygen.
[src:chemical/chemical] Here, one molecule of methane reacts with two molecules of oxygen gas to yield one molecule of carbon dioxide and two molecules of liquid water.
[src:chemical/chemical] This particular chemical equation is an example of complete combustion.
[src:chemical/chemical] The numbers in front of each quantity are a set of stoichiometric coefficients which directly reflect the molar ratios between the products and reactants.
[src:chemical/chemical] Stoichiometry measures these quantitative relationships, and is used to determine the amount of products and reactants that are produced or needed in a given reaction.
[src:chemical/chemical] Describing the quantitative relationships among substances as they participate in chemical reactions is known as *reaction stoichiometry*.
[src:chemical/chemical] Because of the well-known relationship of moles to atomic weights, the ratios that are arrived at by stoichiometry can be used to determine quantities by weight in a reaction described by a balanced equation.
[src:chemical/chemical] This is called *composition stoichiometry*.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In grammar, a **noun** is a word that represents a concrete or abstract thing, like living creatures, places, actions, events, qualities, states of existence, and ideas.
[src:chemical/common-noun] To summarize this, nouns signify an object or idea.
[src:chemical/common-noun] A noun may serve as an object or subject within a phrase, clause, or sentence.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In linguistics, nouns constitute a lexical category (part of speech) defined according to how its members combine with members of other lexical categories.
[src:chemical/common-noun] The syntactic occurrence of nouns differs among languages.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In English, prototypical nouns are common nouns or proper nouns that can occur with determiners, articles and attributive adjectives, and can function as the head of a noun phrase.
[src:chemical/common-noun] According to traditional and popular classification, pronouns are distinct from nouns, but in much modern theory they are considered a subclass of nouns.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Every language has various linguistic and grammatical distinctions between nouns and verbs.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Word classes (parts of speech) were described by Sanskrit grammarians from at least the 5th century BC.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In Yāska's *Nirukta*, the noun (*nāma*) is one of the four main categories of words defined.
[src:chemical/common-noun] The Ancient Greek equivalent was *ónoma* (ὄνομα), referred to by Plato in the *Cratylus*, and later listed as one of the eight parts of speech in *The Art of Grammar*, attributed to Dionysius Thrax (2nd century BC).
[src:chemical/common-noun] The term used in Latin grammar was *nōmen*.
[src:chemical/common-noun] All of these terms for "noun" were also words meaning "name".
[src:chemical/common-noun] The English word *noun* is derived from the Latin term, through the Anglo-Norman *nom* (other forms include *nomme*, and *noun* itself).
[src:chemical/common-noun] The word classes were defined partly by the grammatical forms that they take.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In Sanskrit, Greek, and Latin, for example, nouns are categorized by gender and inflected for case and number.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Because adjectives share these three grammatical categories, adjectives typically were placed in the same class as nouns.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Similarly, the Latin term *nōmen* includes both nouns (substantives) and adjectives, as originally did the English word *noun*, the two types being distinguished as *nouns substantive* and *nouns adjective* (or *substantive nouns* and *adjective nouns*, or simply *substantives* and *adjectives*).
[src:chemical/common-noun] Many European languages use a cognate of the word *substantive* as the basic term for *noun* (for example, Spanish *sustantivo*, "noun").
[src:chemical/common-noun] Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation *s.* or *sb.* instead of *n.*, which may be used for proper nouns or neuter nouns instead.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In English, some modern authors use the word *substantive* to refer to a class that includes both nouns (single words) and noun phrases (multiword units that are sometimes called *noun equivalents*).
[src:chemical/common-noun] It can also be used as a counterpart to *attributive* when distinguishing between a noun being used as the head (main word) of a noun phrase and a noun being used as a noun adjunct.
[src:chemical/common-noun] For example, the noun *knee* can be said to be used substantively in *my knee hurts*, but attributively in *the patient needed knee replacement*.
[src:chemical/common-noun] A noun can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In the following, an asterisk (*) in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Nouns have sometimes been characterized in terms of the grammatical categories by which they may be varied (for example gender, case, and number).
[src:chemical/common-noun] Such definitions tend to be language-specific, since different languages may apply different categories.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Nouns are frequently defined, particularly in informal contexts, in terms of their semantic properties (their meanings).
[src:chemical/common-noun] Nouns are described as words that refer to a *person*, *place*, *thing*, *event*, *substance*, *quality*, *quantity*, etc., but this manner of definition has been criticized as uninformative.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Several English nouns lack an intrinsic referent of their own: *behalf* (as in *on behalf of*), *dint* (*by dint of*), and *sake* (*for the sake of*).
[src:chemical/common-noun] Moreover, other parts of speech may have reference-like properties: the verbs *to rain* or *to mother*, or adjectives like *red*; and there is little difference between the adverb *gleefully* and the prepositional phrase *with glee*.
[src:chemical/common-noun] A functional approach defines a noun as a word that can be the head of a nominal phrase, i.e., a phrase with referential function, without needing to go through morphological transformation.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Nouns can have a number of different properties and are often sub-categorized based on various of these criteria, depending on their occurrence in a language.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Nouns may be classified according to morphological properties such as which prefixes or suffixes they take, and also their relations in syntax – how they combine with other words and expressions of various types.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Many such classifications are language-specific, given the obvious differences in syntax and morphology.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In English for example, it might be noted that nouns are words that can co-occur with definite articles (as stated at the start of this article), but this could not apply in Russian, which has no definite articles.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In some languages common and proper nouns have grammatical gender, typically masculine, feminine, and neuter.
[src:chemical/common-noun] The gender of a noun (as well as its number and case, where applicable) will often require agreement in words that modify or are used along with it.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In French for example, the singular form of the definite article is *le* for masculine nouns and *la* for feminine; adjectives and certain verb forms also change (sometimes with the simple addition of *-e* for feminine).
[src:chemical/common-noun] Grammatical gender often correlates with the form of the noun and the inflection pattern it follows; for example, in both Italian and Romanian most nouns ending in *-a* are feminine.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Gender can also correlate with the sex or social gender of the noun's referent, particularly in the case of nouns denoting people (and sometimes animals), though with exceptions (the feminine French noun *personne* can refer to a male or a female person).
[src:chemical/common-noun] In Modern English, even common nouns like *hen* and *princess* and proper nouns like *Alicia* do not have grammatical gender (their femininity has no relevance in syntax), though they denote persons or animals of a specific sex.
[src:chemical/common-noun] The gender of a pronoun must be appropriate for the item referred to: "The *girl* said the *ring* was from *her* new *boyfriend*, but *he* denied *it* was from *him*" (three nouns; and three gendered pronouns: or four, if this *her* is counted as a possessive pronoun).
[src:chemical/common-noun] Many nouns have both countable and uncountable uses; for example, *soda* is countable in "give me three sodas", but uncountable in "he likes soda".
[src:chemical/common-noun] Some nouns have both concrete and abstract meanings: *art* usually refers to something abstract ("Art is important in human culture"), but it can also refer to a concrete item ("I put my daughter's art up on the fridge").
[src:chemical/common-noun] A noun might have a literal (concrete) and also a figurative (abstract) meaning: "a brass *key*" and "the *key* to success"; "a *block* in the pipe" and "a mental *block*".
[src:chemical/common-noun] Similarly, some abstract nouns have developed etymologically by figurative extension from literal roots (*drawback*, *fraction*, *holdout*, *uptake*).
[src:chemical/common-noun] Many abstract nouns in English are formed by adding a suffix (*-ness*, *-ity*, *-ion*) to adjectives or verbs (*happiness* and *serenity* from the adjectives *happy* and *serene*; *circulation* from the verb *circulate*).
[src:chemical/common-noun] Illustrating the wide range of possible classifying principles for nouns, the Awa language of Papua New Guinea regiments nouns according to how *ownership* is assigned: as alienable possession or inalienable possession.
[src:chemical/common-noun] An alienably possessed item (a tree, for example) can exist even without a possessor.
[src:chemical/common-noun] But inalienably possessed items are necessarily associated with their possessor and are referred to differently, for example with nouns that function as kin terms (meaning "father", etc.), body-part nouns (meaning "shadow", "hair", etc.), or part–whole nouns (meaning "top", "bottom", etc.).
[src:chemical/common-noun] A noun phrase (or **NP**) is a phrase usually headed by a common noun, a proper noun, or a pronoun.
[src:chemical/common-noun] The head may be the only constituent, or it may be modified by determiners and adjectives.
[src:chemical/common-noun] For example, "The dog sat near Ms Curtis and wagged its tail" contains three NPs: *the dog* (subject of the verbs *sat* and *wagged*); *Ms Curtis* (complement of the preposition *near*); and *its tail* (object of *wagged*).
[src:chemical/common-noun] "You became their teacher" contains two NPs: *you* (subject of *became*); and *their teacher*.
[src:chemical/common-noun] For example, in the sentence "Gareth thought she was weird", the word *she* is a pronoun that refers to a person just as the noun *Gareth* does.
[src:chemical/common-noun] The word *one* can replace parts of noun phrases, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.
[src:chemical/common-noun] But *one* can also stand in for larger parts of a noun phrase.
[src:chemical/common-noun] For example, in the following example, *one* can stand in for *new car*.
[src:chemical/common-noun] Nominalization is a process whereby a word that belongs to another part of speech comes to be used as a noun.
[src:chemical/common-noun] This can be a way to create new nouns, or to use other words in ways that resemble nouns.
[src:chemical/common-noun] In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics denoted by the adjective.
[src:chemical/common-noun] is a worldwide association of political parties.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] A **noun phrase** – or **NP** or **nominal (phrase)** – is a phrase that usually has a noun or pronoun as its head, and has the same grammatical functions as a noun.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Noun phrases are very common cross-linguistically, and they may be the most frequently occurring phrase type.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Noun phrases often function as verb subjects and objects, as predicative expressions, and as complements of prepositions.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] One NP can be embedded inside another NP; for instance, *some of his constituents* has as a constituent the shorter NP *his constituents*.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] In some theories of grammar, noun phrases with determiners are analyzed as having the determiner as the head of the phrase, see for instance Chomsky (1995) and Hudson (1990).
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Some examples of noun phrases are underlined in the sentences below.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Noun phrases can be identified by the possibility of pronoun substitution, as is illustrated in the examples below.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] A string of words that can be replaced by a single pronoun without rendering the sentence grammatically unacceptable is a noun phrase.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] As to whether the string must contain at least two words, see the following section.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Traditionally, a phrase is understood to contain two or more words.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The traditional progression in the size of syntactic units is *word < phrase < clause*, and in this approach a single word (such as a noun or pronoun) would not be referred to as a phrase.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] However, many modern schools of syntax – especially those that have been influenced by X-bar theory – make no such restriction.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Here many single words are judged to be phrases based on a desire for theory-internal consistency.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] A phrase is deemed to be a word or a combination of words that appears in a set syntactic position, for instance in subject position or object position.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The words in bold are called phrases since they appear in the syntactic positions where multiple-word phrases (i.e. traditional phrases) can appear.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] This practice takes the constellation to be primitive rather than the words themselves.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The word *he*, for instance, functions as a pronoun, but within the sentence it also functions as a noun phrase.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The phrase structure grammars of the Chomskyan tradition (government and binding theory and the minimalist program) are primary examples of theories that apply this understanding of phrases.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Other grammars such as dependency grammars are likely to reject this approach to phrases, since they take the words themselves to be primitive.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] For them, phrases must contain two or more words.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] A typical noun phrase consists of a noun (the head of the phrase) together with zero or more dependents of various types.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The allowability, form and position of these elements depend on the syntax of the language in question.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] In English, determiners, adjectives (and some adjective phrases) and noun modifiers precede the head noun, whereas the heavier units – phrases and clauses – generally follow it.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] This is part of a strong tendency in English to place heavier constituents to the right, making English more of a head-initial language.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Japanese and Turkish) are more likely to place all modifiers before the head noun.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Other languages, such as French, often place even single-word adjectives after the noun.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Noun phrases can take different forms than that described above, for example when the head is a pronoun rather than a noun, or when elements are linked with a coordinating conjunction such as *and*, *or*, *but*.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] For more information about the structure of noun phrases in English, see English grammar § Phrases.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Noun phrases typically bear argument functions.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] That is, the syntactic functions that they fulfill are those of the arguments of the main clause predicate, particularly those of subject, object and predicative expression.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] They also function as arguments in such constructs as participial phrases and prepositional phrases.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Sometimes a noun phrase can also function as an adjunct of the main clause predicate, thus taking on an adverbial function, e.g.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The situation is complicated by the fact that in some contexts a noun phrase may nonetheless be used without a determiner (as in *I like big houses*); in this case the phrase may be described as having a "null determiner".
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] In the original X-bar theory, the two respective types of entity are called noun phrase (NP) and N-bar (N, N′).
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Thus in the sentence *Here is the big house*, both *house* and *big house* are N-bars, while *the big house* is a noun phrase.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] In the sentence *I like big houses*, both *houses* and *big houses* are N-bars, but *big houses* also functions as a noun phrase (in this case without an explicit determiner).
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] In some modern theories of syntax, however, what are called "noun phrases" above are no longer considered to be headed by a noun, but by the determiner (which may be null), and they are thus called *determiner phrases* (DP) instead of noun phrases.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] This analysis of noun phrases is widely referred to as the *DP hypothesis*.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] It has been the preferred analysis of noun phrases in the minimalist program from its start (since the early 1990s), though the arguments in its favor tend to be theory-internal.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] By taking the determiner, a function word, to be head over the noun, a structure is established that is analogous to the structure of the finite clause, with a complementizer.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Apart from the minimalist program, however, the DP hypothesis is rejected by most other modern theories of syntax and grammar, in part because these theories lack the relevant functional categories.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Dependency grammars, for instance, almost all assume the traditional NP analysis of noun phrases.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] For illustrations of different analyses of noun phrases depending on whether the DP hypothesis is rejected or accepted, see the next section.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The representation of noun phrases using parse trees depends on the basic approach to syntactic structure adopted.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The layered trees of many phrase structure grammars grant noun phrases an intricate structure that acknowledges a hierarchy of functional projections.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Dependency grammars, in contrast, since the basic architecture of dependency places a major limitation on the amount of structure that the theory can assume, produce simple, relatively flat structures for noun phrases.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The representation also depends on whether the noun or the determiner is taken to be the head of the phrase (see the discussion of the DP hypothesis in the previous section).
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] Below are some possible trees for the two noun phrases *the big house* and *big houses* (as in the sentences *Here is the big house* and *I like big houses*).
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The following trees represent a more complex phrase.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] For simplicity, only dependency-based trees are given.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The first tree is based on the traditional assumption that nouns, rather than determiners, are the heads of phrases.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The head noun *picture* has the four dependents *the*, *old*, *of Fred*, and *that I found in the drawer*.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The tree shows how the lighter dependents appear as pre-dependents (preceding their head) and the heavier ones as post-dependents (following their head).
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The second tree assumes the DP hypothesis, namely that determiners serve as phrase heads, rather than nouns.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] The determiner *the* is now depicted as the head of the entire phrase, thus making the phrase a determiner phrase.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] There is still a noun phrase present (*old picture of Fred that I found in the drawer*) but this phrase is below the determiner.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] An early conception of the noun phrase can be found in *First work in English* by Alexander Murison.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] In this conception a noun phrase is "the infinitive of the verb" (p.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] 146), which may appear "in any position in the sentence where a noun may appear".
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] For example, *to be just is more important than to be generous* has two underlined infinitives which may be replaced by nouns, as in *justice is more important than generosity*.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] This same conception can be found in subsequent grammars, such as 1878's *A Tamil Grammar* or 1882's *Murby's English grammar and analysis*, where the conception of an X phrase is a phrase that can stand in for X.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] By 1912, the concept of a noun phrase as being based around a noun can be found, for example, "an adverbial noun phrases is a group of words of which the noun is the base word, that tells the time or place of an action, or how long, how far, or how much".
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] By 1924, the idea of a noun phrase being a noun plus dependents seems to be established.
[src:chemical/noun-phrase] For example, "Note order of words in noun-phrase--noun + adj. + genitive" suggests a more modern conception of noun phrases.
